llar financial work, to men’s committees, to women smugglers. At stake are interdependencies that bind borrowers and lenders, financial technologies, and Paraguayan development in ways that structure both global inequality and global opportunity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBusinesswomenzParaguay. 0aMicrofinancexSocial aspectszParaguay. 0aMicrofinancezParaguay. 0aSmugglingxEconomic aspectszParaguay. 0aWomen-owned business enterprisesxEconomic aspectszParaguay. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aborrowing and lending.  abusiness and finance in paraguay.  aeconomics in paraguay.  afemale entrepreneurs.  afeminist business.  afeminization of business.  afeminization of finance.  afeminization of lending.  afinancial technology.  agender studies.  agroup loans for women.  amicrocredit.  amicrofinance.  amicroloans.  apink collar finance.  asmall loans.  asocial collateral.  asouth american commerce.  awoman owned business.  awomen in business.  awomen in finance.  awomen smugglers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028704440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096220040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962200/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY